===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|爿|肉|alt2=⺼|t1=bed; small table|t2=meat|寸|t3=hand|ls=psc|c1=p|c2=s|c3=s}} – to offer meat as tribute. Besides pronunciation, 爿 may partly indicate a small cutting board and/or sacrificial table on which the meat is placed. The sacrificial meat and the hand together form the shape [[𪧷]], which is similar but unrelated to [[有]].

The {{lang-lite|zh|sc=Hani|⺼}} component is on its side, hence resembles {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|夕}} with an added dot; compare {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|祭}}, {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|然}}.

[[w:Shuowen Jiezi|''Shuowen'']] erroneously considers the phonetic component of {{lang-lite|zh|sc=Hani|將}} to be {{och-l|醬|sauce}} (abbreviated).

===Etymology===
A conflation of two roots: “to take; to hold” and “will; be going to; near”.

; “to take; to hold” (Pronunciations 1, 2 and 3)
: {{der|zh|sit}}: compare {{cog|bo|འཆང|t=to hold, to keep, to carry}}.

; “will; be going to; near” (Pronunciation 1)
: {{der|zh|aav}}: compare {{cog|km|ចង់|t=to want, to wish; to approach, to draw near; about to (do something), on the point of}} < {{cog|okz|caṅa||to wish, to want}}. Cognate with {{och-l|且|about to; on the point of; moreover; also}} ({{zh-ref|Wu, 2015}}).

; anteposed object introductory particle
: {{zh-ref|Pulleyblank (1995)}} notes that 將 as well as several other particles like {{och-l|唯}} and {{och-l|必}} could in Early Classical Chinese topicalize a noun phrase, including predicate objects who are recapitulated with the verb by the pronoun {{och-l|是}}, leading effectively to a construction in the form of "將 O 是 V" ("to V O"), which he notes is superficially similar to the later colloquial usage of 將 and 把.

